</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="81FB2A2EFF97FFF6A055BD57FC46F478" box="[830,915,1581,1607]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="10.[136,229,1610,1632]" captionTargetBox="[306,1282,279,1582]" captionTargetId="figure-58@10.[302,1286,275,1586]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 3. A) Opuntia megapotamica (orange flowers). B) Parodia arnostiana (yellow flowers). C) P. herteri (pink flowers). D) P. linkii (yellow flower). E) P. mammulosa (yellow flower). F) P. nothorauschii. G) P. ottonis(flores yellow flower). H) P. ritteriana(yellow flower). I) P. tenuycilindrica. J) Wigginsiasellowii (yellow flower). K) W. langsdorffii (pale-yellow flower). L) W. turbinata (yellow flower). Pictures by A. S. Oliveira." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6415615" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6415615/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="162">Fig. 3L</figureCitation>
), associated with rocky outcrops and saxicolous vegetation. They are plants of globular to cylindrical habit of 
<quantity id="DE389B4EFF97FFF6A02ABD2AFC6FF454" box="[833,954,1616,1643]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" metricValueMax="2.0" metricValueMin="0.6" pageId="9" pageNumber="162" unit="cm" value="13.0" valueMax="20.0" valueMin="6.0">6 to 20 cm</quantity>
in diameter, densely tomentose in the apex, with tuberculated ribs, bell-shaped yellow flowers approximately 
<quantity id="DE389B4EFF97FFF6A001BD0EFC74F4B0" box="[874,929,1652,1679]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="162" unit="cm" value="5.0">5 cm</quantity>
in length, fruits (glabrous) pink or red, hidden by the tom, devoid of trichomes or bristles. Depending on the species, flowering begins in October–December, bearing fruit soon after.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="197F36ABFF97FFF6A3D6BD9BFE7FF5B4" blockId="9.[136,1452,1400,2075]" pageId="9" pageNumber="162">
In the SMRB all species found are endemic to the Pampa (
<tableCitation id="54420310FF97FFF6A033BD9BFC7AF4C4" box="[856,943,1761,1787]" captionStart="TABLE 2" captionStartId="5.[136,224,989,1013]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="TABLE 2: Geographic distribution of species found in SMRB in relation to phytophysiognomy, geomorphology and conservation status. Phytophysiognomy: G = Grasslands; SV = Saxicolous vegetation; F = Forest, W = Wetlands. Geomorphology: VH = Volcanic Hills; SH = Sandstone Hills. Conservation Status: EN = Endangered; CR = Critically Endangered; VU = Vunerable; NT = Near Threatened; LC = Least Concern; DD = Deficient Data; NE = Not Evaluated." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/4DBF6623FF9BFFFAA3E3B8A7FD6BF695" pageId="9" pageNumber="162" tableUuid="4DBF6623FF9BFFFAA3E3B8A7FD6BF695">Table 2</tableCitation>
) except for four that are also common to the Atlantic forest. Species of restricted distribution are 
<taxonomicName id="DEC04D28FF97FFF6A181BC7FFC65F520" box="[746,944,1797,1823]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Frailea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="9" pageNumber="162" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="albifusca">
<emphasis id="2BB4EAB9FF97FFF6A181BC7FFC65F520" box="[746,944,1797,1823]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="162">Frailea albifusca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="DEC04D28FF97FFF6A0AABC7FFBF3F520" authorityName="Buining &amp; Brederoo" authorityYear="1973" box="[961,1062,1797,1823]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Frailea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="9" pageNumber="162" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="lepida">
<emphasis id="2BB4EAB9FF97FFF6A0AABC7FFBF3F520" box="[961,1062,1797,1823]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="162">F. lepida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="DEC04D28FF97FFF6A75CBC7FFB03F520" authorityName="Buining &amp; Brederoo" authorityYear="1972" box="[1079,1238,1797,1823]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Frailea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="9" pageNumber="162" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="mammifera">
<emphasis id="2BB4EAB9FF97FFF6A75CBC7FFB03F520" box="[1079,1238,1797,1823]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="162">F. mammifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="DEC04D28FF97FFF6A78CBC7FFA70F520" authorityName="R. Pontes, A. S. Oliveira &amp; Deble" authorityYear="2018" box="[1255,1445,1797,1823]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Frailea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="9" pageNumber="162" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="erythracantha">
<emphasis id="2BB4EAB9FF97FFF6A78CBC7FFA70F520" box="[1255,1445,1797,1823]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="162">F. erythracantha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="DEC04D28FF97FFF6A3E3BC53FEB7F57D" authorityName="Hofacker" authorityYear="1988" baseAuthorityName="Lisal &amp; Kolarik" baseAuthorityYear="1986" box="[136,354,1833,1859]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Parodia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="9" pageNumber="162" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="arnostiana">
<emphasis id="2BB4EAB9FF97FFF6A3E3BC53FEB7F57D" box="[136,354,1833,1859]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="162">Parodia arnostiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="DEC04D28FF97FFF6A21BBC53FDD4F57D" authorityName="D. R. Hunt" authorityYear="1997" baseAuthorityName="F. Ritter" baseAuthorityYear="1979" box="[368,513,1833,1858]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Parodia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="9" pageNumber="162" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="curvispina">
<emphasis id="2BB4EAB9FF97FFF6A21BBC53FDD4F57D" box="[368,513,1833,1858]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="162">P. curvispina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="DEC04D28FF97FFF6A155BC53FD11F57D" authorityName="A. S. Oliveira &amp; R. Pontes" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Lisal &amp; Kolarik" baseAuthorityYear="1986" box="[574,708,1833,1858]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Parodia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="9" pageNumber="162" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ritteriana">
<emphasis id="2BB4EAB9FF97FFF6A155BC53FD11F57D" box="[574,708,1833,1858]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="162">P. ritteriana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which have populations located only in sedimentary and volcanic outcrops, respectively, within the study region, which proves the need for conservation and a management plan for the species’ occurrence areas.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="197F36ABFF97FFF6A3D6BCEFFBA1F5C8" blockId="9.[136,1452,1400,2075]" pageId="9" pageNumber="162">
The floristic diversity of the family is intrinsically related to the edaphic and climatic conditions provided by the stony springs in the Santa Maria River Basin, which constitute a favorable microclimate of intense luminosity, heat and humidity so that species adapted to xeromorphy such as 
<taxonomicName id="DEC04D28FF97FFF6A06BBCA7FCA4F5C8" box="[768,881,2013,2039]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="9" pageNumber="162" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Cactaceae</taxonomicName>
develop in this region.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="197F36ABFF97FFF5A3D6B37BFA87F2E3" blockId="9.[136,1452,1400,2075]" lastBlockId="10.[136,1451,158,221]" lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="163" pageId="9" pageNumber="162">Regarding the populations found, it is noted that there is a lack of knowledge about the conservation of species, especially when there is mining in their areas of occurrence, it has been found in the literature that of the 29 species occurring in SMRB, 9 species are critically endangered. (CR), 9 endangered (EN) and 6 are vulnerable (VU).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
